Comment (src/views/control-implementations/partials/ControlStatementMetadata.vue:47):
**Low — raw array rendering.** `{{ statement.props || 'None' }}` (and `statement.links` below) interpolates the raw array, so a populated statement renders a JSON dump like `[ { "name": "...", "value": "..." } ]`. This behavior was moved verbatim from the old inline template, but since this is a brand-new component it's a good moment to format it — e.g. a `name=value` list for props and the count or hrefs for links, falling back to 'None' when empty (note `[] || 'None'` is also truthy, so an empty array renders as `[]`, not 'None').
Replies:
**lisa implementation guidance:** In src/views/control-implementations/partials/ControlStatementMetadata.vue, stop interpolating statement.props and statement.links directly. Add small helper functions in the script: formatProps(props) should return 'None' for missing or empty arrays, otherwise join each prop as name=value when both exist, name when only name exists, value when only value exists, and fall back to 'Property' only if neither exists. formatLinks(links) should return 'None' for missing or empty arrays, otherwise join each link using text if present, else href if present, else rel if present, and fall back to 'Link' only if none exist. Update the template to render {{ formatProps(statement.props) }} and {{ formatLinks(statement.links) }}. Keep the rest of the metadata component layout and the existing Edit button behavior unchanged.

